			<div class="content" id="post-content-4215809">
									

<h3><span>Quick Guides</span></h3>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">►&nbsp;How&nbsp;Magic&nbsp;and&nbsp;Quintessence&nbsp;Works</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">▼&nbsp;Close</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<h4><span>Magic and Quintessence</span></h4>
<p style="text-align: center;">(づ｡◕‿‿◕｡)づ・。*。✧・゜゜・。✧。*・゜゜・✧。・゜゜・。*。・゜*✧</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><sup>*results may vary</sup></p>
<p>Magic is an action that expends quintessence and can be used to, essentially, cheat your way over some obstacle. Quintessence is also tied to health, which makes it incredibly important to manage its use. The drain of quintessence is also correlated to the desired effect, which will be on a case-by-case basis. To perform magic, it is required that the spellbook be counted in Umber's or an Ally's load. The effect of which is completely left up to the imagination of the audience. Just keep in mind that the bigger the effect, the bigger the drain.</p>
<p>Quintessence can take different forms, and so far has been seen to be either Brightmatter or Shadowstuff; the presence of which are going to be dependent on the plot. However, both of these materials are classified as the metaphysical &quot;solids&quot; of light and dark respectively. They don't follow conventional physics and can be malleable, firm, fluid, gaseous, or some other property as the situation calls for. Magic expends quintessence like fuel, effectively changing it from solid matter to arcane energy for spells. Quintessence is also the binder which keeps Umber's existence stable, himself a being derived from magic. When the quintessence is gone, so is Umber.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">►&nbsp;How&nbsp;Load&nbsp;Works</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">▼&nbsp;Close</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<h4><span>Load</span></h4>
<p>Load is essentially the capacity of what Umber can carry on their person by themself. Umber's current load capacity is <strong>6</strong>. Objects will have a determined size, which determines how much of a load they are. Keep in mind that size takes into accout the dimensions and/or weight of the object. Refer to the table below:</p>
<table class="wiki-content-table">
<tr>
<th>Size</th>
<th>Load</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Huge (a trashbin)</td>
<td>5</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Large (a gun)</td>
<td>3</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Medium (a coffee cup)</td>
<td>2</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Small (a pencil)</td>
<td>1</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Tiny (a pinch of dirt)</td>
<td>0</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>Anyone can ask what the size of an object is if you are suggesting it for the inventory. Also there are no tricky workarounds allowed like putting a piece of paper in the book or tying an object to your familiar.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">►&nbsp;How&nbsp;Fog'o'War&nbsp;Works</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">▼&nbsp;Close</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<h4><span>Fog'o'War</span></h4>
<p>Basically this refers to the effect of blurred and unblurred areas in the map that Umber has explored or has yet to explore respectivley. The more you explore, the more map is revealed. Obviously having a physical map on hand (as part of your load) negates this and would reveal the current location entirely. Just looking at a map is not enough to reveal the whole enchilada, as that would defeat the purpose of carrying a map in the first place and just drives us into meta gaming.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">►&nbsp;How&nbsp;Allies&nbsp;Work</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">▼&nbsp;Close</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<h4><span>Allies</span></h4>
<p>Allies are basically people (&quot;people&quot; being a relative term here) in Umber's immediate group that he can call on, interact with, or ask favors. An NPC, if you like that term. The most obvious benefit is that they have their own load and can carry extra things that Umber can't. Also their participation is completely up to the interactions between them and Umber. They can affect the situation both positively or negatively depending on what is happening, so anticipating how an ally is going to react is something that will need to be considered. Keep in mind that allies can switch to enemies and vice versa, so interactions and relationships are key.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
